# Software Development Lifecycle (SDLC)

Follow this lifecycle for all development work in the Conscious Pregnancy project.

## 0. Before Starting ANY Work (CRITICAL)

**You MUST complete these steps before planning or writing code:**

1. **Delegate to the planner subagent** (`.cursor/agents/planner.md`) - For any non-trivial task, use the planner subagent to investigate and create an implementation plan
2. **Check for existing Linear ticket** - Ask the user: "Is there an existing Linear ticket for this work?"
3. **Understand the full workflow** - Your plan must incorporate this entire SDLC

### Ticket Check

Before creating a new ticket:

- **If ticket EXISTS**: Get the ticket ID and reference it throughout your work
- **If NO ticket**: Create one following the Linear Ticket Skill (`.cursor/skills/linear-ticket/SKILL.md`)
- **If UNSURE**: Ask the user to clarify before creating a duplicate

### Why Tickets Matter

- Enables traceability: Sentry error -> ticket -> PR -> code
- Allows team visibility into work in progress
- Provides context for code reviewers

## 1. Planning & Research

Before writing any code, thoroughly plan your work:

- **Use the planner subagent** (`.cursor/agents/planner.md`) for deep investigation and plan creation
- **Use all available tools** to research, gather information, and deeply understand the problem
- **Create a detailed plan** that incorporates this SDLC

### Key Investigation Tools

| Tool | Purpose |
| --- | --- |
| `gh` (GitHub CLI) | Create pull requests, read prior pull requests, review PR history, check CI status |
| Linear MCP | Create/update tickets, search issues, track work |
| `sentry-cli` | Find production errors, investigate exceptions |

## 2. Test-Driven Development (TDD)

Follow TDD best practices, especially the **Red-Green-Refactor** loop:

1. **Red**: Write a failing test that defines the expected behavior
2. **Green**: Write the minimum code necessary to make the test pass
3. **Refactor**: Clean up the code while keeping tests green

### Always Observe Your Code Running

**Every line of code you write should be observed executing** - during TDD, in the browser, error states, and logs. Exceptions: obscure edge cases for type checker satisfaction.

**Trigger all code paths:**

- **Conditionals**: Find ways to make the app enter each branch (if/else, switch cases)
- **Error handlers**: Trigger the error state to verify catch blocks execute correctly
- **Edge cases**: Test boundary conditions and empty states

If you write a conditional or error handler but never observe it executing, you don't know if it works. Tests passing is not enough - see the actual behavior in the running application.

### Verify Tests Actually Fail

After your test passes, verify it can fail:
1. Modify source code to break it
2. Confirm test fails as expected
3. Undo the change

Tests that always pass are worthless.

### Test Coverage

Aim for **90%+ test coverage**. The only code that should remain untested is:

- Obscure edge cases that may never realistically happen
- Code written purely to satisfy the type checker

### Test Types

- **Unit tests & Integration tests**: Use TDD for these tests during development (Bun test runner)
- **End-to-end tests**: Create an e2e test for new features or bug fixes to verify the full user flow (Playwright)

## 3. Browser Testing for UI Changes

If your work impacts the user-facing website, use a browser to verify functionality and check for regressions.

### Starting the Development Environment

```zsh
# Single terminal - start the Next.js dev server
cd frontend && bun dev
```

The app will be available at `http://localhost:3000`.

### Important Notes

- **Turbopack enabled** - fast hot module replacement for instant feedback
- **Logs go to stdout** - monitor the terminal for errors and clues
- **Auto-restart** - the dev server reloads on file changes automatically

## 4. Code Quality Checks

All code changes must pass these checks before proceeding.

From the `frontend/` directory:

```zsh
# Run ALL checks before committing (in this order):
bun run format:fix    # Formatting auto-fix (oxfmt) -- ALWAYS RUN FIRST
bun run lint:fix      # Linting with auto-fix (oxlint)
bun run knip          # Dead code / unused exports check
bun run typecheck     # Type checking (tsgo)
bun test              # Unit tests (Bun test runner)
```

**NEVER skip `bun run format:fix`** -- it must run before every commit. Formatting failures will break CI.

**Do NOT run `bun run build` locally** -- it is slow and redundant. The build is verified by CI after pushing. Monitor CI checks on the PR instead.

## 5. Pull Request & CI Process

Once your task is complete locally and all checks pass:

### Creating the Pull Request

Follow the **Pull Request Skill** (`.cursor/skills/pull-request/SKILL.md`) for:

1. **Branch naming** - Include ticket ID: `cp-123-brief-description`
2. **Commit messages** - Reference ticket ID: `fix: description [CP-123]`
3. **PR description** - Must include:
   - Problem description
   - **Linear ticket link** (for tracking)
   - **Sentry issue links** (if applicable, for context)
   - Root cause analysis
   - Solution explanation
   - Testing instructions

### Cross-Linking Requirements

Every PR must link to:

- Linear ticket (for tracking)
- Sentry issues (for context on production errors)

After creating the PR, add a comment to the Linear ticket with the PR URL.

### Waiting for CI (CRITICAL)

Your task is **NOT complete** until all CI checks pass.

**Use sleep commands to wait for CI:**

```bash
# Wait 3 minutes, then check status
sleep 180 && gh pr checks

# If checks still running, wait another 3 minutes
sleep 180 && gh pr checks
```

Repeat the wait cycle until all checks pass or fail.

### CI Checks

The CI pipeline typically runs:

1. Lint
2. Type check (tsgo)
3. Unit tests (Bun)
4. Build (Next.js)

### Handling Cursor Bug Bot (CRITICAL)

The Cursor bug bot automatically reviews PRs and leaves comments. You MUST:

1. **Read ALL bug bot comments** - Don't skip any
2. **Address EVERY issue raised** - Fix the code or explain why it's not needed
3. **Push fixes** - Each fix triggers a new CI run
4. **Wait for CI again** - Use the sleep method above
5. **Repeat until clean** - No bug bot issues should remain

### Completion Criteria

Work is **ONLY complete** when ALL of these are true:

- [ ] Linear ticket exists and is linked in PR
- [ ] All CI checks are green
- [ ] No unresolved Cursor bug bot comments
- [ ] No outstanding PR review comments
- [ ] PR description follows the Pull Request Skill
- [ ] Linear ticket has a comment with PR URL
